**Full Research Context (Complete Synthesis):**
Dependency confusion attacks exploit package managers fetching malicious public packages named like private internals. Core concepts: Software supply chain; Dependency confusion (name squatting); Package managers (npm, pip, RubyGems); Public registries (npmjs.com, PyPI); Private registries (Artifactory, Nexus).
Attack Vectors: Attacker publishes malicious pkg to public registry matching private name; package mgr resolves public first/fallback (e.g., npm checks npmjs before private if not scoped). Risks: Malicious code exec in builds/dev, supply chain compromise.
Real-world: Alex Birsan (2021) hit Shopify/Uber ($100k+ bounties); AWS (capital-one-like?); Microsoft (ua-parser-js hijack).
Prevention Best Practices: 1) Scoped packages (@org/pkg); 2) Private registry priority (.npmrc: registry=https://private; scope=@org); 3) Lockfiles (package-lock.json, Pipfile.lock); 4) Auth/verify (tokens, domain scoping); 5) Logs/audit (npm ls --parseable); 6) SCA tools (Dependabot alerts, npm audit, Snyk, Sigstore signing). Standards: OWASP Software Supply Chain Security, SLSA Framework Levels 2-4.
Sources: Alex Birsan 'Dependency Confusion' (socket.dev), Sonatype Blog, OWASP.org, npmjs.com/docs/configuring-npm, pypa.io/pip.
